column91: The main problem came from 2's and 1's that were written in similar ways.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_15_3) AppleWebKit/605.1.15 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/13.0.5 Safari/605.1.15
column91: Different ways in which people may write the same number. As well as similarities between certain numbers and letters.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_15_4) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.149 Safari/537.36
column91: because the numbers were written/drawn in a way that resembled the way another number had been drawn

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.149 Safari/537.36
column91: Ones and twos are tricky, because each person's handwriting style is different. While as a human I was able to discern that a particular number was clearly a one, the feedback the computer had received from other humans made that number look two-like to the computer.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.149 Safari/537.36
column91: The handwriting was not legible therefore it was difficult to tell what the number was.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.149 Safari/537.36
column91: Some of the numbers could be interpreted as letters, ie o instead of 0.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.149 Safari/537.36
column91: I only noticed one failure which I think was a reasonable mistake to make. The way the 1 had been drawn looked very similar to some of the 2s labelled correctly by humans. Handwriting is so varied, it would be impossible to get 100% accuracy.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_15_3) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.149 Safari/537.36
column91: The way some number ones and number twos had been written in the human labeled images were very similar. It would be hard to tell them apart.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_15_4) AppleWebKit/605.1.15 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/13.1 Safari/605.1.15
column91: This happened only once. The way 1 was written was very similar to 2. Even a human coder may not be completely certain about this number.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.162 Safari/537.36
column91: It only failed to identify one number which was number 1 written with a line across the bottom as it thought it was a 2. A lot of people do add the line across the bottom so perhaps it requires more learning on the differences between 1 and 2

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.149 Safari/537.36
column91: to see whether an individual would disagree with the programme

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/70.0.3538.102 Safari/537.36 Edge/18.18363
column91: It failed on the number 1 and guessed it was a number 2. to be fair to the programme they did look like 2's so I blame the fault on the humans

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64; rv:74.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/74.0
column91: It failed because the numbers were written similarly to another number--it was a 1 written with top and bottom tails that did look reasonably similar to a 2. Because this is a nonstandard way of writing the number 1, it probably didn't have enough data to know that 1 could be written that way and therefore went with the closest thing it could find, which was a 2. Including additional data that included the number 1 being written in that way would probably improve it, although I'm not sure the problem would ever go away 100%.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_14_6) AppleWebKit/605.1.15 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/13.0.5 Safari/605.1.15
column91: I think because the way in which people write their numbers differs greatly from person to person and therefore some numbers, which are in fact different, may appear similar depending on the handwriting.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.162 Safari/537.36
column91: It did not pick up on the crucial aspect of a straight line as an indication of certain numbers.  The angle at certain parts of some numbers makes a huge difference.  This is obviously based on the context of the digit however.  Alone some things are difficult to judge and if you are expecting a numerical digit in the English language it helps a lot.  If I pondered the possibility of for example Arabic letters it made it harder and we do commonly use some greek letters in maths even when using say an English textbook.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_15_3) AppleWebKit/605.1.15 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/13.0.5 Safari/605.1.15
column91: Because the handwriting wasn't great and looked too similar to other numbers. Arguably this is unavoidable in certain instances.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.149 Safari/537.36
column91: did not recognise due to having not been programme to compute numbers written in certain ways many people write things different

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_14_6) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/80.0.3987.132 Safari/537.36
column91: Sometimes the numbers aren't written as expected, and there's no number that it looks like it can compare it to. The human differentiation in writing/drawing numbers means the program can't always pick up which number it is supposed to look like.
